ms.ipp.iterator

Class NestedIterator<T,U>

  • java.lang.Object
    • ms.ipp.iterator.NestedIterator<T,U>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of elements returned by the original Iterator
    U - The type of elements returned by the created Iterator
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Iterator<U>

    public class NestedIterator<T,U>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Iterator<U>
    An Iterator which offers a "flattened-up" view on hierarchical structures with two levels. For example, given a List<List<T>> list, we can define an Iterator which iterates over all elements of list.get(0), then proceeds to the iterating over list.get(1), etc., as follows: 
     Iterator it = new NestedIterator, T>(list.iterator(), i -> i.iterator());
    The template parameters in <List<T>, T> are strictly for information purposes and may be dropped. With the convenience method flatten(Iterator), the above code may be written in a more expressive manner: 
     Iterator it = NestedIterator.flatten(list.iterator());
    For another example, imagine you have a List<String> departments and a member function
    List<Person> getEmployees(String department) in the caller class. Then, 
     Iterator it = new NestedIterator(departments.iterator(), s -> getEmployees(s).iterator());
    iterates over all employees in all departments. Again, there is more expressive manner of writing this by using iterable(Iterator, Function): 
     Iterator it = NestedIterator.iterable(departments.iterator(), this::getEmployees);
    The third frequently encountered example is to combine several Iterators into one. Suppose we have Iterator<T> it1, it2, it3. Then 
     Iterator it = NestedIterator.merge(it1, it2, it3);
    iterates over all elements in it1, then in it2, and finally in it3. The NestedIterator can be generalised to an arbitrary number of hierarchy levels. This is done in Tree and its implementations.
    Author:
    mykhailo.saienko
